# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ridgeline-plots
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] In statistics, **probability density estimation** or simply **density estimation** is the construction of an estimate, based on observed data, of an unobservable underlying probability density function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The unobservable density function is thought of as the density according to which a large population is distributed; the data are usually thought of as a random sample from that population.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] A variety of approaches to density estimation are used, including Parzen windows and a range of data clustering techniques, including vector quantization.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The most basic form of density estimation is a rescaled histogram.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] We will consider records of the incidence of diabetes.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The data were collected by the US National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] In this example, we construct three density estimates for "glu" (plasma glucose concentration), one conditional on the presence of diabetes, the second conditional on the absence of diabetes, and the third not conditional on diabetes.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The conditional density estimates are then used to construct the probability of diabetes conditional on "glu".
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The "glu" data were obtained from the MASS package of the R programming language.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] Within R, `?Pima.tr` and `?Pima.te` give a fuller account of the data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The mean of "glu" in the diabetes cases is 143.1 and the standard deviation is 31.26.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The mean of "glu" in the non-diabetes cases is 110.0 and the standard deviation is 24.29.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] From this we see that, in this data set, diabetes cases are associated with greater levels of "glu".
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] This will be made clearer by plots of the estimated density functions.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The first figure shows density estimates of *p*(glu | diabetes=1), *p*(glu | diabetes=0), and *p*(glu).
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The density estimates are kernel density estimates using a Gaussian kernel.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] That is, a Gaussian density function is placed at each data point, and the sum of the density functions is computed over the range of the data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] From the density of "glu" conditional on diabetes, we can obtain the probability of diabetes conditional on "glu" via Bayes' rule.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] For brevity, "diabetes" is abbreviated "db." in this formula.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] The second figure shows the estimated posterior probability *p*(diabetes=1 | glu).
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] From these data, it appears that an increased level of "glu" is associated with diabetes.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] A very natural use of density estimates is in the informal investigation of the properties of a given set of data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] Density estimates can give a valuable indication of such features as skewness and multimodality in the data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] In some cases they will yield conclusions that may then be regarded as self-evidently true, while in others all they will do is to point the way to further analysis and/or data collection.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] An important aspect of statistics is often the presentation of data back to the client in order to provide explanation and illustration of conclusions that may possibly have been obtained by other means.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] Density estimates are ideal for this purpose, for the simple reason that they are fairly easily comprehensible to non-mathematicians.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] More examples illustrating the use of density estimates for exploratory and presentational purposes, including the important case of bivariate data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] Density estimation is also frequently used in anomaly detection or novelty detection: if an observation lies in a very low-density region, it is likely to be an anomaly or a novelty.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] In statistics, kernel density estimation (KDE) is the application of kernel smoothing for probability density estimation, i.e., a non-parametric method to estimate the probability density function of a random variable based on *kernels* as weights.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] KDE answers a fundamental data smoothing problem where inferences about the population are made based on a finite data sample.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] In some fields such as signal processing and econometrics it is also termed the Parzen–Rosenblatt window method, after Emanuel Parzen and Murray Rosenblatt, who are usually credited with independently creating it in its current form.
[src:ridgeline-plots/density-estimation] One of the famous applications of kernel density estimation is in estimating the class-conditional marginal densities of data when using a naive Bayes classifier, which can improve its prediction accuracy.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] In statistics, **kernel density estimation** (**KDE**) is the application of kernel smoothing for probability density estimation, i.e., a non-parametric method to estimate the probability density function of a random variable based on *kernels* as weights.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] In some fields such as signal processing and econometrics it is also termed the **Parzen–Rosenblatt window** method, after Emanuel Parzen and Murray Rosenblatt, who are usually credited with independently creating it in its current form.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Let $\mathbf {x} =\left(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},...\right)$ be independent and identically distributed samples drawn from some univariate distribution with an unknown density *f* at any given point x.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] We are interested in estimating the shape of this function *f*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] A kernel with subscript h is called the *scaled kernel* and defined as *K**h*(*x*) = ⁠1/*h*⁠ *K*(⁠*x*/*h*⁠).
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Intuitively one wants to choose h as small as the data will allow; however, there is always a trade-off between the bias of the estimator and its variance.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The choice of bandwidth is discussed in more detail below.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] A range of kernel functions are commonly used: uniform, triangular, biweight, triweight, Epanechnikov (parabolic), normal, and others.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The Epanechnikov kernel is optimal in a mean square error sense, though the loss of efficiency is small for the kernels listed previously.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Due to its convenient mathematical properties, the normal kernel is often used, which means *K*(*x*) = *ϕ*(*x*), where ϕ is the standard normal density function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The construction of a kernel density estimate finds interpretations in fields outside of density estimation.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] For example, in thermodynamics, this is equivalent to the amount of heat generated when heat kernels (the fundamental solution to the heat equation) are placed at each data point locations *xi*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Similar methods are used to construct discrete Laplace operators on point clouds for manifold learning (e.g. diffusion map).
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Kernel density estimates are closely related to histograms, but can be endowed with properties such as smoothness or continuity by using a suitable kernel.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] For the histogram, first, the horizontal axis is divided into sub-intervals or bins which cover the range of the data: In this case, six bins each of width 2.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Whenever a data point falls inside this interval, a box of height 1/12 is placed there.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] If more than one data point falls inside the same bin, the boxes are stacked on top of each other.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] For the kernel density estimate, normal kernels with a standard deviation of 1.5 (indicated by the red dashed lines) are placed on each of the data points *xi*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The kernels are summed to make the kernel density estimate (solid blue curve).
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The smoothness of the kernel density estimate (compared to the discreteness of the histogram) illustrates how kernel density estimates converge faster to the true underlying density for continuous random variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The bandwidth of the kernel is a free parameter which exhibits a strong influence on the resulting estimate.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] To illustrate its effect, we take a simulated random sample from the standard normal distribution (plotted at the blue spikes in the rug plot on the horizontal axis).
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The grey curve is the true density (a normal density with mean 0 and variance 1).
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] In comparison, the red curve is *undersmoothed* since it contains too many spurious data artifacts arising from using a bandwidth *h* = 0.05, which is too small.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The green curve is *oversmoothed* since using the bandwidth *h* = 2 obscures much of the underlying structure.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The black curve with a bandwidth of *h* = 0.337 is considered to be optimally smoothed since its density estimate is close to the true density.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] An extreme situation is encountered in the limit $h\to 0$ (no smoothing), where the estimate is a sum of n delta functions centered at the coordinates of analyzed samples.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] In the other extreme limit $h\to \infty$ the estimate retains the shape of the used kernel, centered on the mean of the samples (completely smooth).
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] where *o* is the little o notation, and n the sample size (as above).
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] where ${\textstyle R(g)=\int g(x)^{2}\,dx}$ for a function *g*, ${\textstyle m_{2}(K)=\int x^{2}K(x)\,dx}$ and $f''$ is the second derivative of f and K is the kernel.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Neither the AMISE nor the *h*AMISE formulas can be used directly since they involve the unknown density function f or its second derivative $f''$ .
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] To overcome that difficulty, a variety of automatic, data-based methods have been developed to select the bandwidth.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Several review studies have been undertaken to compare their efficacies, with the general consensus that the plug-in selectors and cross validation selectors are the most useful over a wide range of data sets.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Substituting any bandwidth h which has the same asymptotic order *n*−1/5 as *h*AMISE into the AMISE gives that AMISE(*h*) = *O*(*n*−4/5), where *O* is the big *O* notation.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] It can be shown that, under weak assumptions, there cannot exist a non-parametric estimator that converges at a faster rate than the kernel estimator.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Note that the *n*−4/5 rate is slower than the typical *n*−1 convergence rate of parametric methods.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] If the bandwidth is not held fixed, but is varied depending upon the location of either the estimate (balloon estimator) or the samples (pointwise estimator), this produces a particularly powerful method termed adaptive or variable bandwidth kernel density estimation.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Bandwidth selection for kernel density estimation of heavy-tailed distributions is relatively difficult.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] An h value is considered more robust when it improves the fit for long-tailed and skewed distributions or for bimodal mixture distributions.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Another modification that will improve the model is to reduce the factor from 1.06 to 0.9.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] This approximation is termed the *normal distribution approximation*, Gaussian approximation, or *Silverman's rule of thumb*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] While this rule of thumb is easy to compute, it should be used with caution as it can yield widely inaccurate estimates when the density is not close to being normal.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The estimate based on the rule-of-thumb bandwidth is significantly oversmoothed.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] One difficulty with applying this inversion formula is that it leads to a diverging integral, since the estimate ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is unreliable for large t's.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] To circumvent this problem, the estimator ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is multiplied by a damping function *ψh*(*t*) = *ψ*(*ht*), which is equal to 1 at the origin and then falls to 0 at infinity.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The "bandwidth parameter" h controls how fast we try to dampen the function ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ .
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] In particular when h is small, then *ψh*(*t*) will be approximately one for a large range of t's, which means that ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ remains practically unaltered in the most important region of t's.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] The most common choice for function *ψ* is either the uniform function *ψ*(*t*) = **1**{−1 ≤ *t* ≤ 1}, which effectively means truncating the interval of integration in the inversion formula to [−1/*h*, 1/*h*], or the Gaussian function *ψ*(*t*) = *e**−πt*2.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] where *K* is the Fourier transform of the damping function *ψ*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Thus the kernel density estimator coincides with the characteristic function density estimator.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Namely, M is the collection of points for which the density function is locally maximized.
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] A natural estimator of M is a plug-in from KDE, where $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ are KDE version of $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ .
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Under mild assumptions, $M_{c}$ is a consistent estimator of M .
[src:ridgeline-plots/kernel-density-estimation] Note that one can use the mean shift algorithm to compute the estimator $M_{c}$ numerically.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Probability density is the probability per unit length, in other words.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The (absolute) probability for a continuous random variable to take on any particular value is zero.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Therefore, the value of the PDF at two different samples can be used to infer, in any particular draw of the random variable, how much more likely it is that the random variable would be close to one point compared to the other.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] More precisely, the PDF is used to specify the probability of the random variable falling *within a particular range of values*, as opposed to taking on any one value.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This probability is given by the integral of a continuous variable's PDF over that range, where the integral is the nonnegative area under the density function between the lowest and greatest values of the range.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The PDF is nonnegative everywhere, and the area under the entire curve is equal to one, such that the probability of the random variable falling within the set of possible values is 100%.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The terms *probability distribution function* and *probability function* can also denote the probability density function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] However, this use is not standard among probabilists and statisticians.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] In other sources, "probability distribution function" may be used when the probability distribution is defined as a function over general sets of values or it may refer to the cumulative distribution function (CDF), or it may be a probability mass function (PMF) rather than the density.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] *Density function* itself is also used for the probability mass function, leading to further confusion.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] In general the PMF is used in the context of discrete random variables (random variables that take values on a countable set), while the PDF is used in the context of continuous random variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Both PMF and PDF are fundamental concepts in statistical inference.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Suppose bacteria of a certain species typically live 20 to 30 hours.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The probability that a bacterium lives *exactly* 5 hours is equal to zero.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] A lot of bacteria live for approximately 5 hours, but there is no chance that any given bacterium dies at exactly 5.00... hours.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] However, the probability that the bacterium dies between 5 hours and 5.01 hours is quantifiable.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Then, the probability that the bacterium dies between 5 hours and 5.001 hours should be about 0.002, since this time interval is one-tenth as long as the previous.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The probability that the bacterium dies between 5 hours and 5.0001 hours should be about 0.0002, and so on.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] In this example, the ratio (probability of dying during an interval) / (duration of the interval) is approximately constant, and equal to 2 per hour (or 2 hour−1).
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] For example, there is 0.02 probability of dying in the 0.01-hour interval between 5 and 5.01 hours, and (0.02 probability / 0.01 hours) = 2 hour−1.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This quantity 2 hour−1 is called the probability density for dying at around 5 hours.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Therefore, the probability that the bacterium dies at 5 hours can be written as (2 hour−1) *dt*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This is the probability that the bacterium dies within an infinitesimal window of time around 5 hours, where *dt* is the duration of this window.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] For example, the probability that it lives longer than 5 hours, but shorter than (5 hours + 1 nanosecond), is (2 hour−1)×(1 nanosecond) ≈ 6×10−13 (using the unit conversion 3.6×1012 nanoseconds = 1 hour).
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] There is a probability density function *f* with *f*(5 hours) = 2 hour−1.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The integral of *f* over any window of time (not only infinitesimal windows but also large windows) is the probability that the bacterium dies in that window.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] A probability density function is most commonly associated with absolutely continuous univariate distributions.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Intuitively, one can think of $f_{X}(x)\,dx$ as being the probability of X falling within the infinitesimal interval $[x,x+dx]$ .
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] In the continuous univariate case above, the reference measure is the Lebesgue measure.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The probability mass function of a discrete random variable is the density with respect to the counting measure over the sample space (usually the set of integers, or some subset thereof).
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] It is not possible to define a density with reference to an arbitrary measure (e.g. one can not choose the counting measure as a reference for a continuous random variable).
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Furthermore, when it does exist, the density is almost unique, meaning that any two such densities coincide almost everywhere.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Unlike a probability, a probability density function can take on values greater than one; for example, the continuous uniform distribution on the interval [0, 1/2] has probability density *f*(*x*) = 2 for 0 ≤ *x* ≤ 1/2 and *f*(*x*) = 0 elsewhere.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Not every probability distribution has a density function: the distributions of discrete random variables do not; nor does the Cantor distribution, even though it has no discrete component, i.e., does not assign positive probability to any individual point.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] A distribution has a density function if its cumulative distribution function *F*(*x*) is absolutely continuous.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] If a probability distribution admits a density, then the probability of every one-point set {*a*} is zero; the same holds for finite and countable sets.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Two probability densities *f* and *g* represent the same probability distribution precisely if they differ only on a set of Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] In the field of statistical physics, a non-formal reformulation of the relation above between the derivative of the cumulative distribution function and the probability density function is generally used as the definition of the probability density function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] It is possible to represent certain discrete random variables as well as random variables involving both a continuous and a discrete part with a generalized probability density function using the Dirac delta function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] (This is not possible with a probability density function in the sense defined above, it may be done with a distribution.) For example, consider a binary discrete random variable having the Rademacher distribution—that is, taking −1 or 1 for values, with probability 1⁄2 each.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This substantially unifies the treatment of discrete and continuous probability distributions.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The above expression allows for determining statistical characteristics of such a discrete variable (such as the mean, variance, and kurtosis), starting from the formulas given for a continuous distribution of the probability.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] It is common for probability density functions (and probability mass functions) to be parametrized—that is, to be characterized by unspecified parameters.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] A given set of parameters describes a single distribution within the family sharing the functional form of the density.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This normalization factor is outside the kernel of the distribution.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Since the parameters are constants, reparametrizing a density in terms of different parameters to give a characterization of a different random variable in the family, means simply substituting the new parameter values into the formula in place of the old ones.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] For continuous random variables *X*1, ..., *Xn*, it is also possible to define a probability density function associated to the set as a whole, often called **joint probability density function**.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] For *i* = 1, 2, ..., *n*, let *f**X**i*(*x**i*) be the probability density function associated with variable *Xi* alone.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This elementary example illustrates the above definition of multidimensional probability density functions in the simple case of a function of a set of two variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] If the probability density function of a random variable (or vector) *X* is given as *fX*(*x*), it is possible (but often not necessary; see below) to calculate the probability density function of some variable *Y* = *g*(*X*).
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This is also called a "change of variable" and is in practice used to generate a random variable of arbitrary shape *f**g*(*X*) = *fY* using a known (for instance, uniform) random number generator.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] It is tempting to think that in order to find the expected value E(*g*(*X*)), one must first find the probability density *f**g*(*X*) of the new random variable *Y* = *g*(*X*).
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The values of the two integrals are the same in all cases in which both *X* and *g*(*X*) actually have probability density functions.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] It is not necessary that *g* be a one-to-one function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] In some cases the latter integral is computed much more easily than the former.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] See Law of the unconscious statistician.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Here *g*−1 denotes the inverse function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This follows from the fact that the probability contained in a differential area must be invariant under change of variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] For functions that are not monotonic, the probability density function for y is $\sum _{k=1}^{n(y)}\left|{\frac {d}{dy}}g_{k}^{-1}(y)\right|\cdot f_{X}{\big (}g_{k}^{-1}(y){\big )},$ where *n*(*y*) is the number of solutions in x for the equation $g(x)=y$ , and $g_{k}^{-1}(y)$ are these solutions.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Suppose **x** is an n-dimensional random variable with joint density *f*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Let $V:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ be a differentiable function and X be a random vector taking values in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , $f_{X}$ be the probability density function of X and $\delta (\cdot )$ be the Dirac delta function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Let Z be a collapsed random variable with probability density function $p_{Z}(z)=\delta (z)$ (i.e., a constant equal to zero).
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Applying the change of variable theorem from the previous section we obtain that $f_{Y,X}(y,x)=f_{X}(\mathbf {x} )\delta {\big (}y-V(\mathbf {x} ){\big )},$ which if marginalized over x leads to the desired probability density function.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This can be derived from a two-way change of variables involving *Y* = *U* + *V* and *Z* = *V*, similarly to the example below for the quotient of independent random variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Given two independent random variables *U* and *V*, each of which has a probability density function, the density of the product *Y* = *UV* and quotient *Y* = *U*/*V* can be computed by a change of variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Then, the joint density *p*(*y*,*z*) can be computed by a change of variables from *U*,*V* to *Y*,*Z*, and *Y* can be derived by marginalizing out *Z* from the joint density.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This method crucially requires that the transformation from *U*,*V* to *Y*,*Z* be bijective.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] The above transformation meets this because *Z* can be mapped directly back to *V*, and for a given *V* the quotient *U*/*V* is monotonic.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This is similarly the case for the sum *U* + *V*, difference *U* − *V* and product *UV*.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Exactly the same method can be used to compute the distribution of other functions of multiple independent random variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] Given two standard normal variables *U* and *V*, the quotient can be computed as follows.
[src:ridgeline-plots/probability-density-function] This is the density of a standard Cauchy distribution.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] A **small multiple** (sometimes called **trellis chart**, **lattice chart**, **grid chart**, or **panel chart**) is a series of similar graphs or charts using the same scale and axes, allowing them to be easily compared.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] It uses multiple views to show different partitions of a dataset.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] The term was popularized by Edward Tufte.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] In the example, the departmental salary expense is charted by month with a dashed line indicating the average for each department.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] The scales on each panel are different to emphasize the relative change over time compared to the range.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Standardizing the scales could provide insight into comparisons in magnitude between the different departments.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Two independent Y axes may be utilized when presenting data with different numeric scales in each panel.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Muybridge's work not only proved for the first time that all four of a horse's hooves left the ground during gallop (see upper central plates), but it also broke new ground in terms of artistic expression and became foundational to the development of the motion picture.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Muybridge went on to produce many more examples of small multiples showing animal locomotion through the medium of stop-motion photography, including boys playing leapfrog and a bison cantering.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Adjacent is a chart showing the population broken down by occupation, including a count of those attending school, according to the 1870 Census.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] This graphic is innovative in its use of both a treemap display and a latticed layout of small multiples.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Additional examples appearing in the *Atlas* include side-by-side geographic maps showing the changes in population over time, as well as tiled mosaic charts showing population demographic breakdowns, and diverging bar graphs showing deaths broken down by age and gender, tiled by state.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Small multiples are a popular technique in cartographic design for multivariate mapping.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] As with the small multiple chart, each panel uses the same underlying two-dimensional space, but in this case that is a geographic space.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Typically, the variables being mapped are of a similar type, such as types of agricultural products, so that the same strategy of map symbol can be used on each panel, enabling rapid comparison between the maps.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Another common use of small multiples is to show change in spatial patterns over time, as an alternative to an animated map.
[src:ridgeline-plots/small-multiple] Several tests of the effectiveness of each method have generally concluded that they have distinct advantages, with animation being better for seeing trends, especially movement, and small multiples being better for making comparisons between times.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:ridgeline-plots/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
